<br>
If the game did not have guidlines set by the alignments it would turn into a highly controversial and debated RP enviroment.  Making RP consistency a real chore to maintain.<br>
<br>
Look all over this forum at the RP debates, all are do to the people who want to step outside the alignment guidelines provided to us.  Without them we cannot hope to have an enviroment that is true for all in the community.  Having the limitations that this is just a game, I think we need the set alignments to allow for smooth RP and gameplay. <br>
<br>
At any rate play like you want, it's your dime.  This is just my opinion.      <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=shaveil>Shaveil</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.epicadventures.net/pic/covicon.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/6/03 7:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Drama</span><hr size=1> Ack!  Sorry to see you go Inthul.  I had just started getting to know you and very much enjoyed role playing with you.  As one who has cancelled his account and thrown away EQ boxes, discs and documentation before because of a relationship gone sour with one other person, I can truly understand your actions.  However, you should know that people are people no matter what game you end up playing.  You are just as likely to run into similar disappointing situations in Asheron's Call 2 in my opinion.  At least I know why you left the Plane of Growth so quickly yesterday.  *frowns*  Take care. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=544939">Shaveil</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
Beguiling for The Nameless from birth</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dididaryth>Didi D Aryth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Worshipping Tallonar since 3160</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/6/03 7:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://users.bigpond.net.au/stbt/didi/a_didisig.gif height=120 width=120></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Drama</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>A lot of this &quot;drama&quot; would be alleviated if people would just stop taking &quot;alignment&quot; so seriously and begin to judge characters based on IC actions, not on a flawed and now dead alignment code.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> Possibly.  But a lot MORE drama would then be created by people disagreeing with the decisions.  And a hell of a lot more work for the poor recruitment officers.  It's hard enough to get to know a recruit and judge their character and fit into the guild before recruiting.  Now we have to observe and judge their every action also?  Make sure they're not secretly killing Nektulos guards when nobody's looking?  Oh wait - you wrote a story where that Nektulos guard murdered your mother.  Now it's RP, that's OK for you to camp him for weeks, you're still evil.  Or what about the folks who aren't great story writers, but who still enjoy roleplay?  Not everybody is an author.  So let's say LoS recruits an 'evil' halfling druid who's written no stories to make his tale publically known, just quietly worked on faction and told his tale to those who ask.  The druid starts running around with LoS tags and the officers get bombarded with nonstop tells, he gets grief, everybody gets miserable, and since realistically very few people will have time to get to know him and make their own decisions, it comes down to &quot;so-and-so is evil because Didi says so&quot;.  It's a nice little theory in an ideal world, Isharra, but it makes recruitment a logistical nightmare, and also sets the recruiters into the position of being arbitrary judge and jury of evilness - not a good place to be.<br>
<br>
One way or another, you have to set fixed guidelines for recruitment.  Agreeing to abide by the original alignment system is one of the easiest.  Limitation by race (e.g. the Halfheight Heroes) is another.  But there has to be some clear rule that is plain and evident to all, so when I say &quot;sorry, evil_druid_01, I'm not recruiting you,&quot; I can point to the rules and say &quot;and that's why&quot;.  Then when concerned_citizen_02 says &quot;Didi, why is evil_ranger_02 in the League?&quot; I can point again and say &quot;there are the rules, he fits them&quot;, and it will be plain to all who enquire that my judgement has not been swayed by favoritism or bias.  <br>
<br>
It comes down to practicality.  Our time is limited.   We must choose our rules and live by them, whatever they may be.  Would it be better to judge each case separately?  Maybe, and maybe it would be more true to RL, but in a game where time is limited and officers' time is already stretched, it is simply impractical.  You could perhaps manage it with a small guild of casual, non-raiding roleplayers - something the size of Twilight Bastion, for example.  But it would soon grow impractical.<br>
<br>
For those curious, a complete list of the acceptible evil races/classes/gods under the old alignment rules is posted on the LoS application guidelines.  <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub33.ezboard.com/fleagueofshadowsfrm8.showMessage?topicID=8.topic">pub33.ezboard.com/fleague...ID=8.topic</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
